{{draft}}{{User:Immanuelle/Japanese Imperial Rituals updated}}

'''Kashikodokoro''' (かしこどころ、けんしょ{{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|p=2}}) is a place in the [[Japan|Japanese]] [[Emperor]]'s [[imperial court]] where the sacred mirror ({{ill|Yata no Kagami|ja|八咫鏡}}), one of the [[Three Sacred Treasures of Japan]] and the spirit of [[Amaterasu Omikami]], is enshrined. In the current [[Imperial Palace]] it is one of the {{ill|Three Palace Sanctuaries|ja|宮中三殿}} {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}.

== Overview ==
The Three Palace Sanctuaries face south, with Kashikodokoro in the center, Kōreiden to the west, and Shinden to the east {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}. Kashikodokoro is considered the most noble building among the three sanctuaries, and its floor is designed to be about one shaku (approximately 30.3 cm) higher than the other two sanctuaries {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}. Each sanctuary is divided into the '''outer sanctuary''' (a room where only [[imperial family]] members are allowed to enter), the '''inner sanctuary''' (a room where only the Emperor and Empress are allowed to enter), and the '''innermost sanctuary''' (a room where [[Amaterasu Omikami]] is enshrined). In the inner sanctuary of Kashikodokoro, there are two {{ill|eternal lamps|ja|常夜灯}} {{Sfnp|皇室編集部|2017|pp=42-43}}.

Historically, it was also called Naishidokoro ({{ill|内侍所|ja|内侍所}}) {{Efn2|神鏡は天皇の御座所に祀られていたが、その後に別殿の[[温明殿]]に移され、内侍所とも称されるようになった{{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=59}}。例えば『{{ill|更級日記|ja|更級日記}}』に内侍所とある{{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=22}}。『{{ill|源氏物語|ja|源氏物語}}』の「{{ill|真木柱|ja|真木柱}}」にも内侍所とあり、11月には祭祀が夥しく行われていたことが反映されている{{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}。なお、別殿に移された時期について、『{{ill|江家次第|ja|江家次第}}』や『{{ill|禁秘抄|ja|禁秘抄}}』は垂仁天皇の代とし、『{{ill|撰集抄|ja|撰集抄}}』は{{ill|宇多天皇|ja|宇多天皇}}の代としている{{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|pp=59-60}}。}}. Various characters were used for "Kashikodokoro" such as "恐所," "畏所," "威所," "尊所," and "貴所" {{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|pp=1-2}}.

Every morning, rituals are conducted by the {{ill|naishoten|ja|内掌典}} and [[Shinto ritual|shinji]] are performed by an envoy dispatched by the Emperor without fail {{Sfnp|松山能夫|1966|pp=121-123}}. Various rituals are also conducted, such as the Emperor's worship on the first day of the month, the [[Kanname-sai|Kanname-sai Kashikodokoro ceremony]] (a grand festival) in October, and the [[Kashikodokoro Misogi|Kashikodokoro Misogi ceremony]] (a minor festival) in December {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|pp=64-92}}.

== History ==
The sacred mirror bestowed by [[Amaterasu Omikami]] has been enshrined within the Imperial Palace by successive generations of emperors according to the "Same Bed, Same Hall" divine decree {{Sfnp|八束清貫|1957|p=4}}. According to the [[Nihon Shoki]], during the reign of the tenth Emperor [[Suinin|Sujin]], the sacred mirror was moved outside the palace for enshrinement due to "living together being uneasy" {{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=53}}{{Efn2|この神鏡は{{ill|垂仁天皇|ja|垂仁天皇}}の代に{{ill|伊勢国|ja|伊勢国}}の{{ill|五十鈴川|ja|五十鈴川}}上流に移され、後に{{ill|伊勢神宮|ja|伊勢神宮}}となる{{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|p=4}}。}}. According to the {{ill|Kogo Shuui|ja|古語拾遺}}, at that time, a duplicate of the sacred mirror was newly cast for enshrinement in the palace {{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=54}}.

From the mid-Heian period onward, with the burning of the {{ill|Dairi|ja|内裏}} and other reasons, temporary palaces were established, and with them, Kashikodokoro was also relocated to appropriate buildings {{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=65}}.

In later years, Kashikodokoro was moved to the {{ill|Shunkoden|ja|春興殿}}, and according to the descriptions in the {{ill|Meimosho|ja|名目抄}} by {{ill|洞院実熙|ja|洞院実熙}}, by the early Muromachi period, Shunkoden had become Kashikodokoro {{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|p=12}}.

From the Jōkyō and Genroku periods of the Edo era, commoners were allowed to visit Naishidokoro on [[Setsubun]], and it became bustling with many visitors {{Sfnp|藤田覚|2018|pp=207-208}}.

In the early Meiji period, it was relocated to Tokyo, and according to a decree in September of the 4th year of Meiji (1871), shrines including Kashikodokoro were constructed {{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|pp=13-15}}.

