[[Category:bump 1-20]] [[Category:refreshing so the massreplace can be done again]] [[Category:Kashiko dokoro]] [[Category:subst:NAMESPACE]] [[Category:subst:NAMESPACE]] [[Category:q--q]] [[en:Kashiko dokoro]][[en:Kashiko dokoro]][[en:Kashiko dokoro]] [[en:Kashiko dokoro]]}}
'''Kashikodokoro''' (賢所, also read as Kensho{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|p=2}}) The '''Kashikodokoro''' is the location within the '''Imperial Palace''' (宮中) of Japan where the '''Yata no Kagami''', one of the '''Three Sacred Treasures''' (三種の神器) and the sacred mirror of the goddess '''Amaterasu''', is enshrined. Currently, it is one of the '''Kyūchū Sanden''' (宮中三殿) in the '''Imperial Palace'''{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}. Before the modern era, it was also called '''Naishidokoro''' (内侍所){{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}.
[[File:Three Palace Sanctuaries.jpg|290px]]
== Overview ==
The '''Kyūchū Sanden''' face south and consist of the '''Kashikodokoro''' at the center, the '''Kōreiden''' to the west, and the '''Shinden''' to the east{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}. Among these three sanctuaries, the '''Kashikodokoro''' is regarded as the most sacred, and its floor is raised approximately one shaku (about 30 centimeters) higher than the others{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}. The structure is divided into three sections: * '''Outer Chamber''' (外陣): Accessible only to members of the Imperial family. * '''Inner Chamber''' (内陣): Accessible only to the Emperor and Empress. * '''Innermost Chamber''' (内々陣): The space where the sacred mirror and '''Amaterasu''' are enshrined.
The '''Inner Chamber''' of the '''Kashikodokoro''' features two '''eternal lamps''' (常夜灯){{Sfn|皇室編集部|2017|pp=42-43}}.
Historically, the '''Kashikodokoro''' was also known as '''Naishidokoro''', referencing the sacred mirror's earlier placement in the '''Onmeiden''' before its relocation to a separate hall{{Efn2|The transition of the sacred mirror from the Emperor’s chamber to the Onmeiden, and later its designation as Naishidokoro, is detailed in several sources, such as the {{ill|Sarashina Nikki|ja|更級日記}} and {{ill|The Tale of Genji|ja|源氏物語}}'s "Makibashira" chapter{{Sfn|橋本富太郎|2005|p=59}}{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}.}}. Various kanji have been used for "Kashikodokoro," including '''恐所''', '''畏所''', '''威所''', '''尊所''', and '''貴所'''{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|pp=1-2}}.
Daily offerings ('''Nikkū''') are conducted in the '''Kashikodokoro''' by the '''Naishoten''', and Imperial rituals ('''Myōchō Goyōhai''') are performed daily without interruption{{Sfn|松山能夫|1966|pp=121-123}}. Additionally, special ceremonies such as the '''Seasonal Festivals''' (旬祭), the '''Kashikodokoro Ritual of Kanname-sai''' in October, and the '''Kashikodokoro Mikagura Ritual''' in December are held annually{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|pp=64-92}}.
== History ==
The sacred mirror, bestowed by '''Amaterasu''', was enshrined in the Imperial Palace per the divine command ('''Same Chamber, Same Hall''') and has been worshiped by successive emperors{{Sfn|八束清貫|1957|p=4}}. According to the '''Nihon Shoki''', during the reign of Emperor Sujin (崇神天皇), the sacred mirror was relocated outside the palace for more secure worship{{Sfn|橋本富太郎|2005|p=53}}{{Efn2|This mirror was eventually moved to the '''Ise Shrine''' during the reign of Emperor Suinin (垂仁天皇){{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|p=4}}.}}.
The '''Kashikodokoro''' experienced relocations due to the destruction of the '''Dairi''' (Imperial Residence) in the Heian period and the establishment of '''temporary residences''' ('''Satodairi'''){{Sfn|橋本富太郎|2005|p=65}}. By the early Muromachi period, the '''Kashikodokoro''' had moved to the '''Shunki-den''', as noted in '''Naimokushō''' by '''Dōin Sanehiro'''{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|p=12}}.
During the '''Ōnin War''', the '''Kashikodokoro''' was temporarily relocated to the '''Muromachi Palace''', where it regained its position as the priority site for Imperial rituals{{Sfn|中本真人|2021|p=52-53}}.
By the Edo period, public access to the '''Kashikodokoro''' was permitted during the '''Setsubun''' festival, attracting numerous visitors{{Sfn|藤田覚|2018|pp=207-208}}.
In 1871, during the Meiji era, the '''Kashikodokoro''' was officially reconstructed as part of the newly relocated '''Imperial Palace'''{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|pp=13-15}}.
