'''Kashiko-dokoro''' (賢所, also read as Kensho{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|p=2}})  
The '''Kashiko-dokoro''' is the location within the '''Imperial Palace''' (宮中) of Japan where the '''[[:en:Yata no Kagami|Yata no Kagami]]''', one of the [[:en:Three Sacred Treasures of Japan|'''Three Sacred Treasures''']] (三種の神器) and the sacred mirror of the goddess '''[[Amaterasu]]''', is enshrined. Currently, it is one of the '''Kyūchū Sanden''' (宮中三殿) in the '''Imperial Palace'''{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}. Before the modern era, it was also called '''Naishidokoro''' (内侍所){{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}.

'''Kashiko-dokoro''' (かしこどころ、けんしょ{{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|p=2}}) is a place in the [[:en:Japan|Japanese]] [[:en:Emperor|Emperor]]'s [[:en:Imperial court|Imperial court]] where the sacred mirror ([[:en:Yata no Kagami|Yata no Kagami]]), one of the [[:en:Three Sacred Treasures of Japan|Three Sacred Treasures of Japan]] and the spirit of [[Amaterasu]], is enshrined. In the current [[:en:Imperial Palace|Imperial Palace]] it is one of the [[:en:Three Palace Sanctuaries|Three Palace Sanctuaries]] {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}.

[[File:Three Palace Sanctuaries.jpg|290px]]

== Overview ==
{{User:Immanuelle/Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace updated}}

== Overview ==  

The [[:en:Three Palace Sanctuaries|Three Palace Sanctuaries]] '''(Kyūchū Sanden)''' face south and consist of the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' at the center, the '''Kōreiden''' to the west, and the '''Shinden''' to the east{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}. Among these three sanctuaries, the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' is regarded as the most sacred, and its floor is raised approximately one shaku (about 30 centimeters) higher than the others{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}. The structure is divided into three sections:  
* '''Outer Chamber''' (外陣): Accessible only to members of the Imperial family.
* '''Inner Chamber''' (内陣): Accessible only to the Emperor and Empress.
* '''Innermost Chamber''' (内々陣): The space where the sacred mirror and '''Amaterasu''' are enshrined.

The '''Inner Chamber''' of the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' features two '''eternal lamps''' (常夜灯){{Sfn|皇室編集部|2017|pp=42-43}}.  

Historically, the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' was also known as '''Naishidokoro''', referencing the sacred mirror's earlier placement in the '''Onmeiden''' before its relocation to a separate hall{{Efn2|The transition of the sacred mirror from the Emperor’s chamber to the Onmeiden, and later its designation as Naishidokoro, is detailed in several sources, such as the [[:en:Sarashina Nikki|Sarashina Nikki]] and [[:en:The Tale of Genji|The Tale of Genji]]'s "Makibashira" chapter{{Sfn|橋本富太郎|2005|p=59}}{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}.}}. Various kanji have been used for "Kashiko-dokoro," including '''恐所''', '''畏所''', '''威所''', '''尊所''', and '''貴所'''{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|pp=1-2}}.  

Daily offerings ('''Nikkū''') are conducted in the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' by the '''Naishoten''', and Imperial rituals ('''Myōchō Goyōhai''') are performed daily without interruption{{Sfn|松山能夫|1966|pp=121-123}}. Additionally, special ceremonies such as the '''Seasonal Festivals''' (旬祭), the '''Kashiko-dokoro Ritual of Kanname-sai''' in October, and the '''Kashiko-dokoro Mikagura Ritual''' in December are held annually{{Sfn|中澤伸弘|2010|pp=64-92}}.  

== Overview ==
The Three Palace Sanctuaries face south, with Kashiko-dokoro in the center, Kōreiden to the west, and Shinden to the east {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=45}}. Kashiko-dokoro is considered the most noble building among the three sanctuaries, and its floor is designed to be about one shaku (approximately 30.3 cm) higher than the other two sanctuaries {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}. Each sanctuary is divided into the '''outer sanctuary''' (a room where only [[:en:Imperial family|Imperial family]] members are allowed to enter), the '''inner sanctuary''' (a room where only the Emperor and Empress are allowed to enter), and the '''innermost sanctuary''' (a room where [[Amaterasu]] is enshrined). In the inner sanctuary of Kashiko-dokoro, there are two [[:en:Nightlight|eternal lamps]] {{Sfnp|皇室編集部|2017|pp=42-43}}.

Historically, it was also called Naishidokoro ({{ill|内侍所|ja|内侍所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/内侍所|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 賢所}}) {{Efn2|神鏡は天皇の御座所に祀られていたが、その後に別殿の[[温明殿]]に移され、内侍所とも称されるようになった{{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=59}}。例えば『[[:en:Sarashina Nikki|更級日記]]』に内侍所とある{{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=22}}。『[[:en:The Tale of Genji|源氏物語]]』の「{{ill|真木柱|ja|真木柱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/真木柱|qq=}}」にも内侍所とあり、11月には祭祀が夥しく行われていたことが反映されている{{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|p=46}}。なお、別殿に移された時期について、『{{ill|江家次第|ja|江家次第|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/江家次第|qq=}}』や『{{ill|禁秘抄|ja|禁秘抄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/禁秘抄|qq=}}』は垂仁天皇の代とし、『{{ill|撰集抄|ja|撰集抄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/撰集抄|qq=}}』は[[:en:Emperor Uda|宇多天皇]]の代としている{{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|pp=59-60}}。}}. Various characters were used for "Kashiko-dokoro" such as "恐所," "畏所," "威所," "尊所," and "貴所" {{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|pp=1-2}}.

Every morning, rituals are conducted by the {{ill|naishoten|ja|内掌典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/naishoten|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 掌典職}} and [[:en:Shinto ritual|shinji]] are performed by an envoy dispatched by the Emperor without fail {{Sfnp|松山能夫|1966|pp=121-123}}. Various rituals are also conducted, such as the Emperor's worship on the first day of the month, the [[Kanname-sai|Kanname-sai Kashiko-dokoro ceremony]] (a grand festival) in October, and the [[Kashiko-dokoro Misogi|Kashiko-dokoro Misogi ceremony]] (a minor festival) in December {{Sfnp|中澤伸弘|2010|pp=64-92}}.

== History ==
The sacred mirror bestowed by [[Amaterasu]] has been enshrined within the Imperial Palace by successive generations of emperors according to the "Same Bed, Same Hall" divine decree {{Sfnp|八束清貫|1957|p=4}}. According to the [[Nihon Shoki]], during the reign of the tenth Emperor [[:en:Suinin|Sujin]], the sacred mirror was moved outside the palace for enshrinement due to "living together being uneasy" {{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=53}}{{Efn2|この神鏡は[[:en:Emperor Suinin|垂仁天皇]]の代に[[:en:Ise Province|伊勢国]]の[[:en:Isuzu River|五十鈴川]]上流に移され、後に[[:en:Ise Shrine|伊勢神宮]]となる{{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|p=4}}。}}. According to the [[:en:Kogo Shūi|Kogo Shuui]], at that time, a duplicate of the sacred mirror was newly cast for enshrinement in the palace {{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=54}}.

From the mid-Heian period onward, with the burning of the {{ill|Dairi|ja|内裏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dairi|qq=}} and other reasons, temporary palaces were established, and with them, Kashiko-dokoro was also relocated to appropriate buildings {{Sfnp|橋本富太郎|2005|p=65}}.

In later years, Kashiko-dokoro was moved to the {{ill|Shunkoden|ja|春興殿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shunkoden|qq=}}, and according to the descriptions in the {{ill|Meimosho|ja|名目抄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meimosho|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} by {{ill|Toin Sanehiro|ja|洞院実熙|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toin Sanehiro|qq=}}, by the early Muromachi period, Shunkoden had become Kashiko-dokoro {{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|p=12}}.

From the Jōkyō and Genroku periods of the Edo era, commoners were allowed to visit Naishidokoro on [[Setsubun]], and it became bustling with many visitors {{Sfnp|藤田覚|2018|pp=207-208}}.

In the early Meiji period, it was relocated to Tokyo, and according to a decree in September of the 4th year of Meiji (1871), shrines including Kashiko-dokoro were constructed {{Sfnp|皇典講究所|1908|pp=13-15}}.

== History ==  

The sacred mirror, bestowed by '''Amaterasu''', was enshrined in the Imperial Palace per the divine command ('''Same Chamber, Same Hall''') and has been worshiped by successive emperors{{Sfn|八束清貫|1957|p=4}}. According to the '''Nihon Shoki''', during the reign of Emperor Sujin (崇神天皇), the sacred mirror was relocated outside the palace for more secure worship{{Sfn|橋本富太郎|2005|p=53}}{{Efn2|This mirror was eventually moved to the '''Ise Shrine''' during the reign of Emperor Suinin (垂仁天皇){{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|p=4}}.}}.  

The '''Kashiko-dokoro''' experienced relocations due to the destruction of the '''Dairi''' (Imperial Residence) in the Heian period and the establishment of '''temporary residences''' ('''Satodairi'''){{Sfn|橋本富太郎|2005|p=65}}. By the early Muromachi period, the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' had moved to the '''Shunki-den''', as noted in '''Naimokushō''' by '''Dōin Sanehiro'''{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|p=12}}.  

During the '''Ōnin War''', the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' was temporarily relocated to the '''Muromachi Palace''', where it regained its position as the priority site for Imperial rituals{{Sfn|中本真人|2021|p=52-53}}.  

By the Edo period, public access to the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' was permitted during the '''Setsubun''' festival, attracting numerous visitors{{Sfn|藤田覚|2018|pp=207-208}}.  

In 1871, during the Meiji era, the '''Kashiko-dokoro''' was officially reconstructed as part of the newly relocated '''Imperial Palace'''{{Sfn|皇典講究所|1908|pp=13-15}}.  

